<HEADLINE>  A FEW USES FOR LEFTOVER EXOTICA  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See also related article on page 1E of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  1 pound lean ground beef; 1/2 cup bread crumbs; 1/4  to 1/3 cup chopped
onions; 1 egg; 1/3 cup barbecue sauce, hoisin sauce or Thai chili sauce;  Mix
all ingredients together. Shape into an oval loaf. Bake on a sheet pan at 375
degrees for about 45 minutes or until an instant-read thermometer reaches 140
degrees. Serves 3-4.; BRAISED WINTER; VEGETABLES; 1/2 pound each carrots,
turnips and potatoes; 1 tablespoon peanut oil; 2 garlic cloves, crushed; 2
teaspoons ginger, chopped; 3 tablespoons hoisin sauce; 1 tablespoon soy sauce;
2 teaspoons sugar; 2/3 cup water;  Peel vegetables. Cut carrots into 2-inch
pieces. Cut turnips and potatoes into 2-inch cubes. Heat oil in a wok. Add
garlic and ginger. Stir-fry 10 seconds. Add carrots, hoisin, soy, sugar and
water. Cover and cook over medium-high heat 3 minutes. Add potatoes and cook 5
minutes more. Add turnips and cook until all vegetables are tender, about 10
minutes. There should be very little sauce left. Serve with any meat roast or
roasted chicken. Serves 4.; CLAMS WITH TOMATO AND BLACK BEAN SAUCE; 2 pounds
clams (or equal amounts of clams and mussels); 1 cup chicken stock or clam
juice; 1 tablespoon fermented black beans, coarsely chopped; 1 1/2 pounds
fresh tomatoes, peeled, seeded and drained in a colander; Salt and pepper to
taste; 4 tablespoons cold butter, cut into small pieces; 1/2 cup basil leaves
for garnish;  Soak and scrub clams to remove sand. Heat stock and black beans
in a pot large enough to easily hold clams. Add clams. Cover and cook over
high heat a few minutes. Uncover and, with a slotted spoon, remove clams as
soon as they open. Set aside, covered. Discard any clams that do not open.;
Reduce liquid in pot by half. Add tomatoes and cook 20 minutes. Season with
salt and pepper. Whisk in butter, a few pieces at a time. Return clams and
heat through. Put in a deep dish and garnish with basil leaves. Serve with
crusty bread or over pasta. Serves 4.; BOILED BEEF DINNER; WITH STAR ANISE; 1
1/2- pound boneless chuck roast or 2- to 2 1/2-pound bone-in roast; 5 star
anise; 2 14-ounce cans chicken or beef stock; Salt and pepper to taste; 1 1/2
pounds potatoes, cut in 1-by-2-inch hunks; 3/4 pound carrots cut in 1- to 1
1/2-inch lengths; 1 bunch scallions, trimmed to a length of about 4 inches;
If using boneless roast, tie with string crosswise at 2-inch intervals. In a
pot large enough to hold meat and vegetables, heat star anise, stock and salt
and pepper. (Warning: Canned stock, especially beef, can be salty.) Simmer 15
minutes, covered. Add beef and cook over low heat 45 minutes, turning once.
Add potatoes and carrots and cook until tender, about 30 minutes. Add
scallions and cook 5 minutes more. Remove meat and vegetables to a platter and
keep warm. Over high heat, reduce liquid in pot while you slice meat. Serve
meat and vegetables in soup plates with broth and bread for dunking. Serves 4.  </TEXT>
