<LEADPARA>  ITALIAN biscotti have become a favorite beverage accompaniment, no matter what
our ethnic origin. Nancy Steele of San Jose wants to make them and now she
can, thanks to the following recipe from Betty Shamus, also of San Jose.;
Shamus said, "My Italian Aunt Mary from New England gave me this recipe that
she used for years. I, too, am Italian and these taste like the real biscotti
I remember as a child growing up in Philadelphia."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BISCOTTI FROM A PHILADELPHIA CHILDHOOD  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Readers' Exchange  </MEMO>
<TEXT>      ITALIAN BISCOTTI;  1 pound margarine (4 sticks);  2 cups sugar;  5 eggs;
1 cup milk;  1 to 2 teaspoons anise extract (or vanilla);  6 cups unbleached
white flour;  6 teaspoons baking powder;  1/2 teaspoon baking soda;   In a
large bowl, cream margarine and sugar together. Add eggs; mix well. Add milk
and anise flavoring; mix well. Sift together flour, baking powder and baking
soda then add to creamy mixture, mixing with wooden spoon until blended.;
Put enough dough on a very lightly floured board to roll gently into a log,
approximately 1-foot long by 2-inches wide. The recipe should make about 7 or
8 of these logs. Place on ungreased cookie sheet (she uses Teflon-coated pans)
and flatten with palm of hand. Place two logs on a cookie sheet.;    Bake in
350 oven till light brown, approximately 10 minutes. Remove from oven and
gently cut into 1-inch slices on a diagonal. Put slices on their sides on
cookie sheets and return to 350 oven to toast until golden brown. Turn each
biscotti over and brown evenly on both sides. Makes at least 5 to 6 dozen
biscotti. Cool thoroughly before storing in tin cans. Stays fresh for 3 to 4
months in tins.;  Vegetarian lasagna;  Anne Randazzo, Santa Cruz, requested a
recipe for vegetable lasagna and we received several responses. The following
recipe was sent by Dolores Gruno. She said she would never have taken the time
to write out this lengthy recipe "if it wasn't exceptional.";    VEGETARIAN
LASAGNA;  1 large onion, chopped;  2 cloves garlic, minced;  1 medium green
pepper, chopped;  4 medium zucchini, coarsely chopped;  1/2 cup celery,
chopped;  5 tablespoons oil;  2 1-pound cans tomatoes;  1 8-ounce can tomato
sauce;  1 6-ounce can tomato paste;  1/2 cup dry vermouth;  1 medium carrot,
chopped;  1/4 cup parsley, chopped;  2 teaspoons oregano;  1 teaspoon basil;
1 teaspoon salt;  1/2 teaspoon thyme;  1/4 teaspoon pepper;  9 wide, curly
lasagna noodles (cooked);  2 cups (1 pound) ricotta cheese;  12 ounces
mozzarella cheese, cut in thin slices;  1 1/2 cups grated Parmesan cheese;
In large frying pan, cook onion, garlic, green pepper, zucchini and celery in
oil over medium heat for 15 minutes, stirring frequently. Stir in tomatoes,
sauce, tomato paste, vermouth, carrot, parsley and seasonings. Bring to boil,
stirring to break up tomatoes. Reduce heat and simmer, covered, for 30
minutes. Remove cover and boil to reduce sauce to measure 5 cups. Spread about
1/4 sauce over bottom of 13- by 9-inch roasting pan. Arrange 3 noodles on top;
dot with 1/3 ricotta; arrange 1/4 mozzarella cheese on top and sprinkle with
1/4 of the Parmesan cheese. Repeat procedure twice. Spread remaining
mozzarella cheese and sprinkle with remaining Parmesan. Bake in a 350 oven 30
to 45 minutes or until bubbly. Let stand 5 minutes before cutting into
squares. Makes 9 servings.;  Calls for help;  Ben Cirelli, San Jose, would
like a recipe for Italian rum cake. He's looking for an old-fashioned variety
that he remembers enjoying in Philadelphia.;    Bill Gravett, San Jose, would
like recipes for scalloped potatoes and crab salad molds.;    Fran Frank, Los
Gatos, is looking for a poppy seed cake recipe.;    Carol Koyama, San Jose,
would like a recipe for "Consumer Report's frozen chicken pot pie recipe,
which was in the magazine at least 15 years ago." She'd also like a similar
one for making small chicken pies that can go from the freezer to the oven or
microwave.  </TEXT>
