<MEMO>  Recipes of the Week  </MEMO>
<TEXT>   1/2 cup water; 1/3 cup butter; 1/2 cup dark brown sugar; 1/4 cup chopped
walnuts; 3/4 teaspoon pure vanilla extract; 1/4 teaspoon pumpkin pie spice;
1/8 teaspoon lemon peel; 1/4 cup dark corn syrup; Dash of allspice;  Wash
potatoes. Place in large saucepan or Dutch oven. Cover with water. Heat to a
boil. Reduce heat, cover and simmer until tender, about 25 to 30 minutes.
Drain and cool. Peel and quarter. Place in buttered 13-by-9-by-2-inch baking
dish. Set aside. Combine remaining ingredients in small saucepan. Simmer 5
minutes. Pour sauce over potatoes. Bake, uncovered, in a 375-degree oven 50
minutes, basting with sauce several times. Makes 5 cups.;   -- From "Best
Recipes for 100 Years" by McCormick/Schilling; CINNAMON-GLAZED ALMONDS; butter
or grease for lining sheet; 2 teaspoons ground cinnamon; 1/2 teaspoon ground
allspice; 1/4 teaspoon salt; 1/8 teaspoon ground red pepper; 2 cans (4 ounces
each) blanched whole almonds (about 1 1/2 cups); 1/2 cup sugar; 2 tablespoons
butter or margarine;  Line a baking sheet with foil; butter or grease; set
aside. In a small cup combine cinnamon, allspice, salt and red pepper; set
aside. In a large skillet combine almonds, sugar and butter. Cook and stir
over medium heat until sugar melts and turns a rich brown color, about 10
minutes. Remove from heat.;   Immediately stir in spice mixture. Quickly
spread almonds onto prepared baking sheet. Cool completely. Break into small
clusters. Store tightly covered, up to 2 weeks. Makes about 2 3/4 cups.; "SHOW
STOPPER" SOUP; 1 10-ounce package frozen chopped spinach; 3 1/2 cups milk,
divided; 1/2 cup drained oysters; 1/4 cup butter; 1/4 cup flour; 1/2 teaspoon
ground nutmeg; 1/4 teaspoon mace; 1/2 teaspoon ground white pepper; 2
teaspoons instant minced onion; 1 can chicken broth; 1 cup whipping cream;
Whipping cream for garnish; Crushed red pepper; Croutons;  Thaw spinach; drain
excess liquid. Pour 1 1/2 cups of the milk into blender jar. Gradually add
spinach, blending until smooth after each addition. Pour into a bowl. Puree
oysters in blender. Add to spinach mixture. Set aside. Melt butter in large
saucepan. Stir in flour and spices; slowly blend in chicken broth. Cook over
medium heat until bubbly.;   Stir in spinach mixture. Add remaining 2 cups of
milk and 1 cup whipping cream. Cook, stirring constantly, over medium heat
until mixture begins to boil. Reduce heat and simmer 2 minutes. Garnish with
dollops of unsweetened whipped cream topped with crushed red pepper and
croutons. Serves 6.;   -- Adapted from "100 Best Recipes for 100 Years" by
McCormick/Schilling; CINNAMON CIRCLES; 1 cup butter, softened; 2/3 cup
confectioners' sugar; 1 teaspoon pure vanilla extract; 2 cups all-purpose
flour (unsifted); 2 teaspoons ground cinnamon; 1/4 teaspoon baking powder; 1/4
teaspoon salt; 1 cup semi-sweet or milk chocolate morsels;  In a large mixing
bowl with electric mixer set at high speed, beat butter until smooth;
gradually add sugar; beat until light and fluffy. Beat in vanilla.;   In a
medium bowl or on a square of waxed paper combine flour, cinnamon, baking
powder and salt. Add to butter mixture, beating until just combined; cover
bowl.;   Chill dough until firm but not hard, about 30 minutes. Preheat oven
to 350 degrees. Shape dough into 3/4-inch balls using 1 tablespoon dough for
each. Place on ungreased cookie sheets 2 1/2 inches apart. Using the bottom of
a floured glass, press each ball into a 2-inch circle.;   Bake until just
golden around the edge, about 6 minutes. Do not overbake. Remove from baking
sheets to a wire rack; cool completely.;   In a small saucepan over very low
heat melt chocolate morsels, stirring constantly. Frost half of each cookie
using a small spatula. Place on a rack to set. Refrigerate in a tightly
covered container. Makes 3 1/2 dozen.; GOLDEN CLOVE GLAZED HAM; 1/2
ready-to-eat ham (about 8 pounds); 1/2 cup brown sugar, packed; 1/8 teaspoon
ground cloves; Whole cloves;  Place ham, fat side up, on rack in roasting pan.
Bake in 325-degree oven 1 1/2 hours. Carefully remove skin. Score fat by
cutting into diamond shapes.;   Combine brown sugar and ground cloves. Spread
this mixture over scored fat and stud each diamond with a whole clove.
Increase temperature to 375 degrees and bake ham 30 minutes longer or until
well glazed. Serves 10 to 12.; MULLING SPICES; Peel from 1 lemon (yellow
portion only); 15 cinnamon sticks; 1 1/2  tablespoons each whole cloves and
allspice; 2 teaspoons whole anise seed, crushed;  With a sharp paring knife or
a potato peeler, remove the peel from the lemon and cut into 1/4-inch wide
strips. Place peel on a baking sheet; bake in a 225-degree oven until dry,
about 1 hour. Cut into 1/4-inch pieces; set aside.;   Place cinnamon sticks, a
few at a time, into a plastic bag; crush into 1-inch slivers using a rolling
pin or mallet. In a medium bowl, place the cinnamon, whole cloves and allspice
with anise seed and lemon peel. Place 2 tablespoons of spice mixture in the
center of a 5-inch square of cheesecloth or muslin; bring corners together and
tie with string to make a pouch. Repeat. Makes 8 spice bags, or 1 cup of spice
mixture.;   Serving Suggestion: Place 1 pouch in 1-quart apple, cranberry or
other juice or red wine. Simmer, covered for 15 or 20 minutes. Serve warm.;
SPICED COCOA; 1 cup powdered hot cocoa mix; 1 teaspoon dried grated orange
peel; 1/4 teaspoon each ground cinnamon and ground nutmeg;  For each 6-ounce
serving, spoon 2 tablespoons of the mix into a cup; stir in until blended 3/4
cup boiling water or hot milk. Recipe may be doubled or tripled.  </TEXT>
