<LEADPARA>  IF YOU'VE blown your financial budget over the holidays, no doubt you blew
your calorie budget as well, eating rich food and holiday treats like butter
cookies and Christmas fudge.;    And like most of us, you're feeling lethargic
and guilt-ridden, having spent New Year's Day in front of the tube watching
parades and ball games and munching on some fatty rich snacks and drinking
beer and soda.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  COUNTING PENNIES AND CALORIES, TOO  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Budget Gourmet
Bruce Aidells, co-author of "Hot Links &amp; Country Flavors" (Knopf, $19.95),
owns Aidells Sausage Co. in Kensington.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     So maybe you're thinking it might be time to cut calories and trim some of
the unwanted side effects that have accumulated around the middle from
Christmas over-indulgence.;    Those of you who read my column regularly might
be saying, "Has he gone bonkers?" Although cost has been a prime objective in
the recipes I give you, we've never discussed calories. But, as they say,
there comes a time . . .;    Just because we're cutting calories doesn't mean
we plan to desert some of our primary directives -- low cost and lots of
flavor.;    To me, diet food does not mean cottage cheese and rice crackers
for dinner, but instead, substantial food with good flavor. When you leave the
table, you should feel satisfied and guilt free, otherwise you might be
sneaking downstairs for that late-night snack of ice cream and cookies.;
And, cutting calories does not mean eliminating meat. Instead, meat should be
used sparingly, taking advantage of its full taste to flavor the other
elements of the dish. There should be lots of vegetables and plenty of
seasonings as well.;    Ingredients such as garlic, onions, leeks and
mushrooms add flavor. Ideal examples of this type of eating are Chinese
stir-fry and Italian pasta dishes.;    The dish I have chosen is pork braised
with Napa cabbage. It's an example of Chinese slow cooking where lots of
flavor is infused into the vegetables. In a Chinese restaurant, this dish
would be cooked and served in a clay braising pot.;    Besides Napa cabbage,
other greens would be equally good in this dish. In fact, any leafy vegetable
is delicious when cooked this way. Try bitter mustard greens or turnip greens,
or milder flavored bok choy, savoy or white cabbage. Serve the dish with
steamed rice.;     PORK BRAISED WITH NAPA CABBAGE;  1 pound pork loin chops,
all fat and bone removed, cut into 1-inch dice;   Salt and pepper to taste;  1
teaspoon Chinese five-spice powder;  2 teaspoons peanut oil;  2 cups thinly
sliced onions;  2 teaspoons minced fresh ginger;  1 teaspoon minced garlic;  1
1/2 pounds Napa cabbage, cut crosswise into 1/2-inch slices;  1/2 cup Chinese
rice wine or medium dry sherry;  1 cup rich chicken stock;  1 cup sliced green
onions or scallions;  2 cups coarsely chopped fresh cilantro;  2 whole star
anise;   Season the meat generously with salt, pepper and the five-spice
powder. Brown the meat in the peanut oil in a heavy frying pan or Dutch oven
for 5 minutes, turning frequently. Remove the meat and add the onions, ginger
and garlic. Cook for 10 minutes over medium heat until they are soft. Add the
cabbage and cook for 2 to 3 minutes, stirring to coat with the pan juices. Add
the wine, chicken stock, 1/4 cup of the green onions, 1 cup of the cilantro
and the star anise. Return the meat to the pan, lower heat to a simmer and
cook for 30 minutes.;    Using a slotted spoon, remove the meat and vegetables
to a serving platter, and keep warm. Turn the heat to high and reduce the
liquid remaining in the skillet until it just begins to turn syrupy. Taste for
salt and pepper, degrease and pour over the meat and cabbage. Garnish with the
remaining green onions and cilantro. Serve with steamed rice. Makes 6
servings. Cost: $.75-$1 per serving.  </TEXT>
