<LEADPARA>  THE cognac industry is very interesting. Like the automobile industry, it is
dominated by a few big companies. Hennessy, Courvoisier, Martell and Remy
Martin produce millions of cases every year of cognac that ranges in quality
from good to superb. Most of the production of these industry giants is in the
cheaper V.S. and V.S.O.P. grades, brandies that have only been aged for four
to six years.;    Delamain is different. This small house, located in Jarnac,
France, a few miles from the city of Cognac, specializes in brandies that are
at least 25 years old, all of which come from Grande Champagne, the most
prestigious "cru" or sub-region of Cognac.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  AGING MOVES COGNAC MAKER ABOVE REST  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Wine
San Francisco-based Anthony Dias Blue is author of "American Wine" and a
writer for numerous trade and consumer magazines.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Long history;  The firm is no newcomer to the production of cognac. The
house was established in the mid-18th century by James Delamain, scion of a
Huguenot family. After years in England, Delamain returned to France in 1759
at the age of 21. He immediately became a cognac shipper, using his family
connections to build a healthy export business in the British Isles.;
Although his company was dissolved in 1817, a new entity, Roullet &amp; Delamain,
was established in 1824, marking the formal founding of what is now Delamain &amp;
Co.;    Today Delamain is run by Alain Braastad-Delamain and Christian
Braastad., former managing director of Courvoisier. Braastad-Delamain is the
10th generation of his family to manage Delamain.;    Delamain produces four
different cognacs: Pale &amp; Dry, Vesper, Tres Venerable and Reserve de la
Famille.;    Pale &amp; Dry Tres Belle Grande Champagne ($50) represents 80
percent of Delamain's production. It is blended from cognacs that average 25
years of age. This brandy is pale gold in color and is made in a delicate,
elegant style. There are lovely flavors of vanilla and oak on the palate. The
mouthfeel is soft with some charming touches of smoke, tea and spice on the
finish. (91);    Serene sips;  Vesper ($90) averages 35 years of age. The
brandy is named after the sixth canonical hour when the evening service or
Vespers are celebrated. The idea is to reflect the "serene, ethereal quality"
of the cognac. It is darker in color and more complex than Pale &amp; Dry. It is
vinous and woody with dense, spicy flavors and a silky texture. (93);    Tres
Venerable ($160) averages 45 to 50 years of age. It is darker still and shows
amazing complexity. On the palate there are hints of anise, honey, dried
apricots, toast and smoke. The flavors are long and lingering. (96);
Reserve de la Famille ($350) is an extremely rare, single-cask cognac
distilled by one grower in the Grande Champagne village of St. Preuil. The
brandy has been 55 years in cask. It is the epitome of the mystique and
essence of cognac. It is spicy and complex with elements of toast, vanilla,
smoke, earth and anise. The flavors are long and intense with great depth and
finesse. (98);    The cognacs of Delamain are not easy to find -- the company
makes only 50,000 cases each year -- but they are worth the extra effort that
searching them out may require. If cognac is the king of brandies, Delamain is
the king of cognacs.  </TEXT>
