<LEADPARA>  Fennel (also called finocchio or anise) gives an exotic flavor to meals. Never
tasted fennel? If you like licorice, you'll probably like it -- once you get
over being surprised that a vegetable can taste like candy. Never seen fennel?
Look along the produce counter for a head of celery that grew lacy,
carrot-like leaves at the top and bulged out squat and round at the bottom. If
it smells of licorice or anise candy, it's fennel.;    Fennel is high in
vitamin A and furnishes calcium, phosphorus and potassium. It's low in
calories. Fennel is available from late summer through early spring. Most
recipes call for trimming the tops, which are reportedly an appetite
suppressant.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  FENNEL
THIS GREEN, LEAFY VEGETABLE
HAS A DISTINCTIVE TASTE.
IF ITS LICORICE FLAVOR APPEALS,
THEN THESE RECIPE WILL, TOO.  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Recipes of the Week  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  FIRST-COURSE FENNEL;   Fennel;   Olive oil;   Salt, freshly ground pepper;
Trim green stalks and tough outer stalks from fresh, top-quality fennel. Cut
into wafer-thin slices. Arrange on a shallow dish and sprinkle with olive oil;
season with salt and pepper. Marinate for 2 hours. Refrigerate if marinated
longer.;    Serve as is as a first course or add to an antipasto tray of
olives, cheeses, cold meats and marinated vegetables such as artichokes and/or
chickpeas.; MICROWAVE-BRAISED; FENNEL;  2 fennel bulbs;  4 tablespoons broth
(chicken or beef) or water;   Seasoned butter;   Trim medium (8-ounce) fennel
bulbs of outer stalks, feathery tops and tough bases.;    Lay bulbs on sides
and trim each until 4 inches long, then quarter lengthwise. Arrange 1 inch
apart in single layer in 2-quart casserole, placing thinner ends toward
center. Add broth or water; cover with lid or vented plastic food wrap.;
Microwave on high 9 to 10 minutes; let stand, covered, 3 minutes. Drain and
season. Serve with seasoned butter. Makes 4 servings.;    -- From "Micro
Ways"; by Jean Anderson and; Elaine Hanna; FENNEL PARMESAN;  4 bulbs of fresh
fennel;  1/4 cup melted butter or margarine;  1/2 cup freshly grated Parmesan
cheese;   Trim green stalks and tough outside stalks from fennel. Trim the
base and slice the fennel from top to bottom into 1/4-inch slices. Cook in
boiling water until tender, about 5 minutes.;    Drain fennel slices; season
with salt and pepper. Place half of fennel in shallow buttered baking dish.
Pour half of melted butter over it and sprinkle with half of cheese. Top with
remaining fennel, butter and cheese. Bake in 425-degree oven 10 minutes. Makes
4 to 6 servings.;  STIR-FRY OF FRESH; FENNEL AND PEAS;  4 to 5 small to medium
fennel bulbs;  2 tablespoons lemon juice;  3 tablespoons olive oil;  3 large
shallots, minced;  2 ounces boiled ham, diced;  1/8 teaspoon dried tarragon,
crumbled;  1 1/2 cup frozen tiny peas, thawed;  2 green onions, cut into
1-inch lengths;  2 tablespoons chopped fennel leaves;   Trim green stalks and
tough outside stalks from fennel; set aside fennel leaves to chop and add
during stir-frying. Slice fennel into thin strips. Combine fennel and lemon
juice in a medium bowl and let stand 10 minutes.;    Heat oil in wok or large
skillet over high heat. Add fennel and shallots and stir-fry, tossing
constantly, about 2 minutes.;    Remove from heat and add ham and tarragon. At
this point, vegetables can be refrigerated until ready to complete the dish.;
  About 5 minutes before serving, return mixture to high heat; toss until very
hot. Add peas, green onions and fennel leaves;  stir-fry just until heated
through. Transfer to serving dish. Makes 6 servings.;    -- From "Vegetables"
in; "Cooking with Bon Appetit"; series (Knapp Press, 1983); FENNEL WITH
TOMATOES; AND GARLIC;  4 fennel bulbs;  1/2 cup olive oil;  1 onion, thinly
sliced;  2 garlic cloves, chopped;  2 or 3 medium tomatoes, peeled and
coarsely chopped or 12-ounce can Italian tomatoes, drained and chopped;   Salt
and freshly ground pepper to taste;   Crumb topping:;  1/2 cup coarse bread
crumbs;  1/2 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese;  1 teaspoon grated lemon
peel;  1 garlic clove, minced;   Trim fennel bulbs, then cut in half
lengthwise and cut into julienne strips.;    Heat oil in a large skillet and
saute the onion a minute or two.;    Add fennel and garlic continue cooking,
stirring occasionally. When fennel begins to brown and is almost cooked, add
the tomatoes and salt and pepper. Lower the heat and cook gently 5 minutes.
This initial cooking can be done in advance.;    Transfer the fennel mixture
to a heavy, shallow dish, such as a gratin dish. Mix the crumbs, cheese, lemon
peel and garlic together and sprinkle over the fennel in the dish. Bake in a
425-degree oven about 15 minutes, until topping is crisp. Makes 4 servings.;
 -- From the Time/Life; series "The Good Cook"; CREAM OF FENNEL AND; ZUCCHINI
SOUP;  1/4 cup vegetable oil;  2 fennel bulbs, thinly sliced, tops reserved;
2 leeks, white part only, thinly sliced;  2 zucchini, sliced;  1/2 teaspoon
dried oregano;  6 cups chicken stock;  1 large potato, peeled and diced;  1
cup heavy cream;   In a medium saucepan, heat oil. Saute fennel, leeks and
zucchini until tender. Add oregano and chicken stock; bring to a boil and add
potato. Simmer, covered, 30 minutes.;    Puree soup with cream, then season to
taste with salt and pepper. Heat to serving temperature. Garnish with chopped
fennel tops. Makes 6 servings.;    -- From "Season to Taste:; Herbs and Spices
in American; Cooking" by Jeannette Ferrary; and Louise Fiszer (Simon and;
Schuster, 1988)  </TEXT>
