<LEADPARA>  THE fermented black beans have been sitting in the door of my refrigerator
since Reagan's first term. They're positioned just above the sweet chili sauce
I bought at a Thai market that has long since gone out of business. And the
tahini just below that? Well, how much hummus can you eat?;   Sound familiar?  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  NOW,...WHAT DO I DO WITH THIS
IS YOUR FRIDGE SCREAMING TO BE CLEARED OF ALL
THOSE HALF-USED JARS OF SAUCES, OILS AND OTHER
CONDIMENTS? TAKE HEART; THOSE FORGOTTEN FOODS CAN
BE USED TO CREATE DISHES WORTH REMEMBERING  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Cover Story; See also related article on page 7E of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Perhaps the dark recesses of your refrigerator contain the remains of a
half gallon of Kansas City barbecue sauce (too bad you're just plain barbecued
out). And what about that Vietnamese fish sauce, those funny little capers
(are they still good?) and the family-size bottle of oyster sauce your husband
bought at Price Club because it's cheaper per ounce than the smaller sizes?;
Now, every time you open the refrigerator or pantry door, a dozen half-used
jars of exotic and not so exotic ingredients stare you in the face and bleat,
"Use me! Use me!";   Don't put up with that jabber. Here's what to do with
those sauces and other condiments so they won't haunt you until the next power
failure forces you to chuck the whole lot of them.;   The first rule of using
ingredient leftovers is to take off your culinary blinders. Who says sesame
oil can be used only in Chinese dishes? The other day on KCBS radio, Narsai
David said he uses sesame oil in his bread recipes instead of vegetable oil.
He reasoned that it would give the bread a nice nutty flavor. And because
sesame oil is pungent, he uses less of it than other oils.;   Rule No. 2 is a
corollary of No. 1. Here's an example. If a vinaigrette is made up of oil and
acid (vinegar and/or lemon juice), why can't you mix sesame oil and red wine
vinegar or olive oil and rice wine vinegar?;   Rule No. 3 is to think balance.
If you're combining sharp flavors such as vinegars and spicy condiments,
mellow out the dish with a dab of cream. Or give it a fresh accent with fresh
herbs.;   Rule No. 4 is to have fun. Hey folks, this is food, not nuclear
disarmament. And if your wife says the fermented black bean vinaigrette smells
fishy, so what?;   Here are a bunch of common and not-so-common leftover
ingredients and how to use them up.;    Barbecue sauce;   If the thought of
one more thing on the grill turns you off, try that leftover barbecue sauce
with pasta. Combine a 28-ounce can of chopped tomatoes with half as much
barbecue sauce. Throw in four ounces of sliced mushrooms sauteed in butter
with some chopped onions. Add fresh chopped basil and simmer 20 minutes. Add a
cup of heavy cream and simmer 10 minutes more.;   In general, use in place of
ketchup for dishes such as meatloaf (good old meatloaf hides a lot of things),
on hot dogs, in taco fillings and in baked beans. Or try on pizzas (especially
if you have a little barbecued chicken left over to go with it).;   Fermented
black beans;   Yes, they smell like they've been taken from the compost heap,
but these salted (and partially decomposed) soy beans add a distinctive accent
to Asian and non-Asian dishes alike. Put them in a vinaigrette with olive oil,
garlic and sherry vinegar and toss with bitter greens. Use with hot pepper and
ginger in a sauce for shellfish. They go surprisingly well with tomatoes in a
sauce for pasta or clams (see recipe). Also, try with garlic in a stir-fry of
hearty greens such as kale. To modify their strong flavor somewhat, soak in
warm water for 30 minutes and drain. Or use in a marinade and discard them.;
Fish sauce;   Nuoc mam if you're Vietnamese, nam pla if you're Thai, and
stinko if you're just about anyone else. The flavor of this fish sauce isn't
as strong as the smell. Since both cultures use it in lieu of soy sauce,
substitute it in recipes that call for soy -- sauces, marinades and dressings.
Use in fish marinades with chopped shallots, sherry vinegar and nut oils such
walnut (if it's a mild fish) or sesame oil.;   Use in recipes that call for
anchovy such as tapenade (a puree of olives, garlic and anchovies). Add a
tablespoon to Caesar salad dressing (not as weird as you think; the original
Caesar had Worcestershire sauce, made with anchovies). Add to garlic, white
wine and olive oil as a quick sauce for steamed mussels. If you need a little
fish stock or clam juice but don't have either, try fish sauce, perhaps
diluted with a little water. And with hot pepper, garlic, rice vinegar, lime
or lemon juice and a little sugar, it makes a great all-purpose dip for almost
any fried food.;   Tahini;   A paste of ground sesame seeds, it's most
commonly used in hummus, the Middle Eastern bean dip. But Asian dishes often
use sesame paste, though Asian sesame paste has toasted seeds. So, try it in
cold, spicy Sichuan noodle dishes with leftover chicken. Add garlic to it and
thin with water and lemon juice for taratoor sauce, great on steamed or fried
vegetables or mixed with roasted sweet peppers. Since it has the look and
consistency of peanut butter, use it as such, spread on toast or bagels with
jam (try with Middle Eastern fig jam). Or put in a satay instead of peanut
butter.;   Sesame and other oils;   Use in combination with other oils,
notably peanut, for salad dressings. Use as a simple marinade for meats, fish
and poultry. Asian food expert Bruce Cost suggests adding a little to
scrambled eggs or mixing it with mustard for basting roast fowl. When you run
out of tahini but not chick peas, make this variation of hummus from "Good &amp;
Plenty" by Victoria Wise and Susanna Hoffman (Harper &amp; Row, $22.95): Puree 2
cups drained chick peas with three cloves garlic in a food processor. Add 1/2
cup olive oil, 1/4 cup sesame oil, 2 tablespoons lemon juice and salt to
taste. Puree.;   Use almond and walnut oils for fish and poultry marinades and
in lightly seasoned vinaigrettes for mild greens or fruit. Avocado oil can be
used in dressings (especially with tomatoes) or to give an extra punch to
guacamole.;    Oyster sauce;   Think of this as the Chinese equivalent of A-1
Sauce and use it accordingly. Terrific on grilled steak. Enliven it with some
hot chilies, soy and sesame oil, if you like. A few dashes accent stir-fried
broccoli or greens such as collards. Or try this dip from "The Encyclopedia of
Asian Food and Cooking" by Jacki Passmore (Hearst Books, $25): In a saucepan,
mix 1 tablespoon each soy and oyster sauce with 2/3 cup chicken stock, 2
tablespoons minced scallions, 1/2 teaspoon sugar and 1 teaspoon cornstarch.
Bring to a boil, then stir until thickened.;    Hoisin sauce;   Use this thick
soybean sauce as is for a barbecue sauce or mix in barbecue sauce recipes
instead of ketchup. You can even use it elsewhere as a sub for ketchup such as
in meatloaf (see recipe). Use as a dip or condiment for roast pork. Spread on
tortillas for a Mexican mu shu pork with carnitas.;   Or, try this delicious
hoisin marinade for chicken adapted from "Ken Hom's East Meets West Cuisine"
(Simon and Schuster, $19.95): Combine two teaspoons fresh thyme leaves, six
tablespoons hoisin sauce, four tablespoons rice wine and two tablespoons olive
oil. Split a chicken in half, lengthwise, and rub marinade on halves. Put in a
dish or plastic bag with rest of marinade and let rest at least one hour.
Grill over indirect heat or bake in a 400 degree oven.;    Chili sauces;
There are many styles, flavors and levels of heat, depending on whether
they're from Thailand, Vietnam or China. Use them as dips for fried foods by
themselves or mixed with soy sauce and chopped scallions. Add to meatloaf
instead of ketchup (or hoisin sauce). Or make a delicious barbecue glaze with
sweet Thai chili, red wine vinegar (to cut some of the sweetness) and fresh
chopped basil. Follow as above for hoisin marinade.;   Wines;   Chinese rice
wine (shaoxing): Substitute for sherry or sherry vinegar in recipes. Use it in
marinades for chicken, fish or pork with scallions, ginger, garlic and soy
sauce.;   Sherry: Use in vinaigrettes, in Chinese dishes that call for rice
wine or to deglaze a pan with sauteed chicken breasts or pork medallions.;
Sake: Use in salad dressings, dips for fried foods (with soy sauce) and
marinades for grilled dishes.;   Madeira or Marsala: Deglaze a pan with
sauteed chicken, turkey or veal. Use Marsala to flavor Italian pastry creams.;
  Port: Poach fruit such as pears.;   Ginger;   When fresh, grate fine and use
in marinades, salad dressings and in salsas with fruit (mangoes are especially
good). Or make a simple chutney with leftover jam. Take a half jar of orange
marmalade, peach or apricot preserves, add a tablespoon of ginger (fresh or
candied) and a teaspoon of mustard seeds, if you have them. You can stick
candied ginger inside cored apples with butter and lemon juice and bake them
for a simple dessert now that apples are coming into season.;   Capers;
Throw them in with sauteed veal, chicken or turkey with lemon juice and white
wine or vermouth.;    Anchovies;   Mix a small amount in salad dressings (it
doesn't have to be Caesar salad). Swirl some into beef or lamb stew. Or mix
with garlic and put into slits made in leg of lamb.;   Pickled jalapenos;
Use on pizzas; in mayonnaise, sour cream or yogurt dips; in fruit chutneys and
salsas; and in pasta sauces.;    Star anise;   The best beef stew I've ever
eaten (at Food Street in Mountain View) was loaded with this. It can
substitute for regular anise or fennel.;   Pimentos or roasted peppers;
Saute in olive oil with onions and garlic and throw in a can of drained
cannellini beans for a great side dish. Or toss with green beans, broccoli or
zucchini.  </TEXT>
