<HEADLINE>  'CANARIES IN THE MINE'
VOLUNTEERS COUNT BUTTERFLIES TO CHECK ENVIRONMENT'S
HEALTH  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Shorter version ran P. 4B Morning Final Edition  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Such were the sacrifices made Saturday morning in the name of science as
part of a national environmentalist group's annual butterfly count. Each year
around Independence Day, volunteers traipse through target areas, from the
Coyote Hills in Fremont down to Alviso, to identify and record the presence of
these delicate and richly variegated insects.;    After a bit, the O.s. --
also known as the woodland skipper -- jumped from Marzo's nose to her
eyeglasses, and then woodland-skipped off. Its presence was duly noted on a
score sheet, beside the anise swallowtails, checkered whites and, yes,
monarchs.;    Lane, the educational director of the Santa Cruz Museum of
Natural History, was leading some of the 15 volunteers who met in the San
Francisco Bay National Wildlife Refuge in Fremont. His charges -- Marzo of
Union City, Barbara Blackford of San Leandro and David Schurr of Oakland --
were equipped with pocket picture books, one net and some butterfly
fundamentals they picked up at a pre-expedition slide show.;    The four spent
most of the day probing plants, squinting into the sun and occasionally
netting the odd insect for inspection.;    The effort does more than simply
tally butterflies, Lane said. "Butterflies are a great tool to assess
environmental change. They're really the canaries-in-the-mine as environmental
indicators.";    And what do they indicate about the environment these days?
His answer isn't exactly a shock: "Loss of habitat.";    "These simple, silly
butterflies are a way to show people what the world is really made of . . .
its phenomenal complexity," he said. "It's a microcosm of everything that's
going on.";    Salt lovers; Throughout the morning, Lane used his position as
butterfly point man to do a little preaching, and teaching, too. For instance,
he explained that butterflies can only drink their nourishment, and that they
like salt.;    So he demonstrated that a woodland skipper often will happily
perch on someone's nose. ("But you didn't really have a sweaty nose," he
assured Marzo.);    Other butterfly facts the volunteers learned:;    (check)
"Butterflies are flying sex machines. All they are here to do is find a mate
and lay some eggs.";    (check) It doesn't hurt a butterfly to pick it up
carefully by the wings. "As long as I don't harm the membrane of the wing,
it'll be fine," Lane said.;    (check) Natural Bridges -- not Pacific Grove --
is the best place to see monarchs.;    The three volunteers, all active in
other environmentalist activities, made a good audience for Lane. But politics
aside, they also expressed appreciation for the butterflies' intrinsic value,
oohing at the fine, colorful details of the temporary captives.;    Before the
day ended, they would visit three more sites, including the Coyote Creek
Riparian Station, proposed site for a baseball stadium for the San Francisco
Giants. The volunteers then turned in their tally sheets to be compiled with
those of others.;    National tally;  The totals won't be known for a couple
of days. The bay results, along with those from 123 other tallies nationwide,
will be evaluated by the Xerces Society, a national conservation organization
devoted to invertebrates.;    "I grew up liking butterflies," said Blackford,
who brought her own net. "I collected them when I was small where I grew up
(in Oakland). There were thousands of them.";    Condos replace habitat;
They're mostly gone now, she added ruefully; they've given way to condominiums
and parking lots.;    Schurr's interest is more recent. As a birdwatcher, "I
decided it's time to learn a little something about butterflies.;    "All this
fits together, you know," he said. "The trees and birds and plants and
butterflies -- it's all one big story."  </TEXT>
