<LEADPARA>  WHILE the best and biggest strawberries make terrific pie and shortcake,
they're really meant for eating out of hand.;    So, try dipping fresh
strawberries. One sweet dip is softened cream cheese mixed with marshmallow
cream to your taste.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  WHAT TO DO WITH THOSE BERRIES
BERRY GOOD STRAWBERRY DIPS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See also related article on page 1E of this section.
Cover Story  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Another easy combination is this ginger vanilla sauce, from the 1988
"Sunset Recipe Annual" (Lane Publishing, $19.95): In a bowl, stir together 3/4
cup vanilla yogurt and 1/4 teaspoon ground ginger.;    Or try honey-almond
dip, from the California Strawberry Advisory Board: 2/3 cup non-fat yogurt; 3
tablespoons toasted, slivered almonds, finely chopped; and 2 1/2 tablespoons
honey. Whisk until smooth.;  STRAWBERRY SHORTCAKE; 2 pints strawberries,
lightly rinsed, hulled, and quartered;  1/4 cup plus 2 teaspoons sugar; 1 cup
whipping cream;  1/4 teaspoon vanilla extract; 8 biscuits (see recipe below);
3 tablespoons unsalted butter, melted;   Toss strawberries in a bowl with the
1/4 cup sugar. Let them stand at room temperature for 2 hours, stirring
occasionally.;    Combine cream with vanilla and the remaining 2 teaspoons
sugar, and whip until thick but soft. Cover the bowl loosely and refrigerate.;
   Just before serving, halve the biscuits and brush the bottoms with melted
butter. Spoon some strawberries with their juice and a dollop (or two) of
whipped cream on each biscuit bottom. Cover with the biscuit tops at an angle.
Serve immediately. Makes eight servings.;    One serving with biscuits: 403
calories; 5 gm protein, 39 gm. carbohydrate, 26 gm. fat, 80 mg. cholesterol
and 280 mg. sodium.;    BISCUITS:; 2 cups all-purpose flour; 1 tablespoon
baking powder; 1 teaspoon sugar;  1/2 teaspoon salt; 5 tablespoons unsalted
butter, cold;  3/4 cup half-and-half;   Heat oven to 450 degrees. In a large
bowl, mix flour, baking powder, sugar and salt. Cut the butter into small
pieces and cut it into the flour using two knives, a pastry blender or your
fingertips until the mixture resembles coarse crumbs.;    Add the
half-and-half and stir gently until the mixture forms a mass. Gather it into a
ball.;    Transfer the dough to a lightly floured surface. Knead it for about
30 seconds, and then pat it out to form a 3/4-inch-thick rectangle. Using a 2
3/4-inch cookie cutter, cut out eight circles, using up all the dough.;
Arrange the biscuits about 1 inch apart on a baking sheet. Bake until puffed
and golden, about 14 minutes. Transfer the biscuits to a wire rack and allow
them to cool.;    -- From "The New Basics" by Julee Rosso and Sheila Lukins
(Workman Publishing, 1989).;    (hbox); STRAWBERRIES EN CHEMISE; 1 cup sifted
powdered sugar (more if needed); 1 teaspoon egg white (more if needed);  1/4
teaspoon fresh lemon juice;  Drops of cognac or more lemon juice, as needed;
24 large fresh strawberries, washed rapidly and laid on a rack;   Place sugar,
egg white and lemon juice in a small high-sided mixing bowl and beat one
minute or more with an electric mixer or wire whisk until sugar forms a stiff
mass that makes stiff points when a bit is lifted in the blades of the beater.
Thin out with a drop or two of cognac or more lemon juice -- the icing should
be thick enough to enrobe strawberries. Holding a berry by its topknot, swirl
it in the frosting to cover 2/3 of the way up its sides, and replace on rack.
May be done an hour in advance. Arrange over strawberry sherbet or ice cream
just before bringing to the table.;    Per strawberry: 21 calories; 0 gm.
protein, 5 gm. carbohydrate, 0 gm. fat, 0 mg. cholesterol and 3 mg. sodium.;
  -- From "Julia Child &amp; Company" (Knopf Publishing, 1978); (hbox); ITALIAN
PEPPERED BERRIES; 1 quart fresh strawberries, about 3 cups sliced;  1/2 cup
sugar, or to taste;  1/4 cup sambuca or other Italian anise-flavored liqueur;
1/4 cup Grand Marnier or other orange-flavored liqueur;  Fresh black
peppercorns in a grinder (set on coarse grind); 3 cups vanilla ice cream,
optional;   Wash, drain, and hull the strawberries, and cut them lengthwise
into 1/4-inch slices. Place in a large glass bowl.;    Ten minutes before
serving, mix in the sugar, liqueurs and 10 grinds of black pepper. Spoon the
ice cream into chilled bowls. Spoon the strawberry mixture over the ice cream.
Grind a little more fresh pepper on top and serve at once. Makes 6 servings.;
  Per serving (without ice cream): 164 calories; 0 gm. protein, 33 gm.
carbohydrate, 0 gm. fat, 0 mg. cholesterol and 3 mg. sodium.;    -- From "A
Celebration of the Seasons" by Steven Raichlen (Poseidon Press, 1988)  </TEXT>
