<LEADPARA>  TIRED of using the same old herbs and spices and getting the same old tastes?
Answering "yes" to the above earns you a ticket to Hebert's lecture on "New
Seasonings For Tomorrow.";    No one knows exactly when our ancestors started
using seasonings to improve the taste of their foods. Man's first taste of
cooked meat presumably came after he accidentally dropped a piece of meat into
a roaring fire, waited until the fire died out and then ate the meat. Later,
he used a stick to remove the meat from the fire before it cooked into ashes.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SURPRISING WAYS TO SEASON YOUR FOOD  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Food and Wine  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     It was the taste of smoky meat that enticed our ancestors to seek seasoning
agents. Salt may have been the first, though some give black pepper primacy.;
  Here are some seasonings to whet your appetite.;    (check) CHOCOLATE -- As
strange as it might seem, chocolate is considered by many chefs to be the
seasoner for meat dishes that call for a rich, dark sauce.;     CHOCOLATE BEEF
STEW;  3 pounds beef, cut into 1/2-inch pieces;  3 tablespoons virgin olive
oil;  1 cup onions, chopped fine;  3 cloves garlic, pressed;   Salt to taste;
1 teaspoon flour;  2 bay leaves;  1 cup white wine;  1/2 cup water;  1
tablespoon white vinegar;  1 tablespoon grated bitter chocolate;   In a deep
saucepan, saute the beef in the olive oil for one minute. Add onion and garlic
and cook 2 minutes. Add flour and salt, mixing well. Add remaining
ingredients, except the chocolate. Cover and cook on low-medium heat until the
meat is tender. Remove the meet with a slotted spoon and keep warm. Add
chocolate to the sauce and stir until well mixed. Strain the sauce and serve
it either on the beef or separately. Serves 6.;    (check) COFFEE -- Billions
of cups of coffee are consumed daily, but few people realize that coffee is a
great seasoner. For example, the next time you make hamburgers, add 1/4 cup of
coffee to the mixture. When you want a special treat try spreading a mixture
of 1/4 cup butter, 2 tablespoons coffee and 1/4 teaspoon crushed anise or
fennel seeds inside your favorite bird. And don't pass up this marinade for
meats.;      COFFEE/RED WINE; MARINADE;  1 cup red wine;  1/2 cup cold coffee;
 1/2 teaspoon dried rosemary;  1/2 teaspoon dried thyme;  1/2 teaspoon dried
chervil;  2 teaspoons salt;  1/4 teaspoon pepper;  1/2 cup vegetable oil;
Combine all ingredients in a glass or ceramic bowl and whisk until well mixed.
Use for marinating lamb, chicken or beef. When grilling, use the marinade for
basting. Yield: 2 cups.;    (check) CAPERS -- Long associated with fancy
European dishes, capers are often overlooked by American chefs. They have a
slight sting that has earned them the name "mountain peppers.";     TURKEY
BREASTS WITH; CAPER/LEMON SAUCE;  12 thin slices raw turkey breast;   Salt and
pepper to taste;   Flour; 3 tablespoons virgin olive oil;  1/4 cup white wine;
 1/4 cup chicken stock;  3 tablespoons capers;  2 tablespoons minced parsley;
1/2 lemon;    Salt and pepper the breasts. Dip them in the flour and saute
them in the oil until they are done. Remove and keep warm. Pour off all but
one tablespoon of oil, then add wine, stock, the juice from the half-lemon,
capers and parsley. Cook over high heat to reduce and thicken the sauce. Pour
over breasts.;    (check) ANCHOVIES -- The clever chef can turn ordinary
dishes into extraordinary dishes with the help of the anchovy. It is the main
ingredient in the making of the great Italian dipping sauce bagna cauda. Most
salad dressings, like this one below, can get a boost from a touch of
anchovy.;     ANCHOVY SALAD DRESSING;  9 tablespoons virgin olive oil; 1 large
clove garlic, pressed; 3 anchovies, minced; 3 tablespoons wine vinegar;   Mix
all ingredients together. Let dressing stand an hour before using. Serves 4.;
  Wine suggestions: With the Chocolate Beef Stew, try 1987 Beaulieu Rutherford
Cabernet Sauvignon, a big, rich wine that is very drinkable now and will get
better in the next five years.;    With the red wine/coffee marinade used for
beef, try a 1988 Clos du Bois Pinot Noir, a spicy wine with cherry and vanilla
overtones. If a fowl was marinated in the mixture, try a 1989 Callaway
"Morning Harvest" Chenin Blanc -- dry, a wine loaded with the fresh flavors of
peaches and pears.;    With the turkey breasts, try the 1987 J. Lohr Seven
Oaks Paso Robles Cabernet Sauvignon, a wine whose aging in American oak has
imparted a vanilla and spice taste.  </TEXT>
