  [Excerpts] An Egyptian diplomatic source in Cairo today
revealed that the United States has embarked on contacts with
Egypt, Saudi Arabia, and the United Arab Emirates, in an attempt
to end the fighting and start a dialogue between the two parties
to the conflict in Yemen. The same source added that the three
Arab states can ensure indirect dialogue between northern and
southern Yemenis and that they have played a mediatory role
since the beginning of the crisis in Yemen. The source said
this mediation aimed at safeguarding Yemen unity without using
force. The same source said these three Arab states will ask the
northerners to agree on a cease-fire in exchange for canceling
the southerners' unilateral declaration of independence.
  Sanaa took this clear U.S. stand seriously. In the wake of
this U.S. stand, Yemeni Planning Minister 'Abd-al-Karim
al-Iryani announced that the government in Sanaa is holding
contacts with some Yemeni Socialist Party [YSP] leaders to agree
on holding a dialogue. Al-Iryani, who is close to President
'Ali 'Abdallah Salih, added that his government is ready for a
cease-fire in exchange for YSP's recognition of Yemen unity,
which was declared in May 1990 and which has been abandoned by
the southerners.
  Al-Iryani said: Following the secession decision, we cannot
deal, hold a dialogue with, or find a place in politics for YSP
Secretary General 'Ali Salim al-Bid or Haydar Abu-Bakr
al-'Attas, who was charged with forming the government of the
new southern state.
  The second factor which could have influenced the Sanaa
decision is Aden's reiteration today that the southern forces
have regained the combat initiative from northern forces that
had infiltrated over the past three weeks of the fighting.
[passage omitted]
  'Abd-al-Karim al-Iryani, who reiterated the northern forces'
control over Abyan, Lahij, and Shabwah Governorates, today
admitted that the objective of entering Aden by all means, which
was announced by 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih, no longer exists. He
said: There might not be a need to enter Aden, as the political
solution could be reached before this. The northern minister
said the Sanaa forces are maintaining their positions on the
eastern front, adding that the northern forces are now preparing
supply bases before moving to the east toward Hadhramaut, where
al-Bid has moved.

